metadata.abstract: The text discusses the comparative analysis of the ordinary repertory from Aquileia and Cividale, highlighting the differences and similarities in liturgical melodies across various sources. It emphasizes the German-Central European orientation of these sources and the challenges in categorizing melodies due to limited data and the use of published catalogs, which may not be entirely reliable. The study suggests that while there is a notable German influence, the Aquileian repertory also shows distinct regional characteristics, necessitating further research to accurately define its unique liturgical identity.

It is striking that the melodies sometimes well represented, though not equally, in north and central Italian sources were not in use in Aquileia at all. The one exception is the Kyrie melody number 31, which beside the source from San Marco, can also be documented from Monza, Benevent, Monte Cassino and Nursia as well. The number of the so-called German-oriented melodies is remarkably less than was in Aquileia. This is more significant in the light of the dissemination, since here such melodies occur sporadically here and there. An exception is the Gloria 19, which on the other hand is missing from Aquileian sources, though this is also a German-oriented melody, well known in central Europe and Italy.

These significant points cannot be connected to any narrower circle of sources, though for drawing such conclusions the number of the analyzed sources is by no means sufficient. However, as a by-product of my statistics, I call attention to the almost complete agreement of the Curiale repertory in Arezzo and Siena. What we have said about the Ostfrankish orientation in the Aquileian repertory is also valid here for the opposite reason. Both the well documented and the sparsely represented melodies confirm the picture of a radical shift towards a quasi-Westfrankish orientation. Finally, on the basis of the Curiale repertory, the characteristic difference between the north and central Italian sources is less than that between the Aquileian and non-Aquileian repertories. Some methodological considerations. First, my categorization defining one group of the melodies as Ostfrankish and the other as Westfrankish may arouse questions or objections. Though I have simply used them as an aid for orientation, I held it important to check these notions as to the validity of them. Namely, I was wondering how my melodies and groups are represented in David Hiley's ordinary catalogue, which is based on 77 English, North French and Sicilian manuscripts, so a markedly Western source group. The result is more than convincing. While the overwhelming majority of my Westfrankish melodies are present in it and occur frequently in its all three groups, the overwhelming majority of those defined by me as German or Central European are missing from it. Exceptions are the Curiale 144 and 151 or the Gloria 25, which, apart from the high number of German documents, can be found in Hiley's English, French and Sicilian sources as well. Nevertheless, in accordance with the overall picture emerging from all collected information, I left them in the German group. In any case, these would by no means modify the plausible proportion of the statistics shown in example 9.
Some closing remarks.

It is perhaps unusual when concerning the observations and conclusions of an examination the author himself warns the audience. I emphasized in advance that the methods used in this paper might be risky to a certain extent. Already the retrieval of the information from the catalogs itself and the quasi-reconstruction of virtual sources by deduction is problematic. Already the material the analysis focused on is not beyond doubt reliable and what is more important it is only to a very limited extent suitable for analyzing the melodies in their real context. And the evaluation of the sources requires several aspects other than the mere occurrence or absence of a certain melody. For example, my own research proved that distribution of the Curiale melodies in the sources the assignment of them to certain feasts the pairing of them, the compilation of cycles from them and last but not least the actual variance of the melodies all together outline a physiognomy of repertory that could be characteristic of a diocese or a consuetudo. The other aspect I neglected here to a certain extent is the chronology. As Camilo Oswald, among others, emphasizes there is a not negligible difference between the 12th and 14th, 15th century state of the Aquileian tradition. Among my observations there may be cases where the differences are the consequences of chronological rather than geographical or institutional distance of the sources. However, the tables, presented in the foregoing, reveal the character of the Aquileian ordinary repertory, show its significant points and are quite promising as to make the picture more accurate and convincing later on by examining the other aspects mentioned above. Thank you very much.

In any case, these would by no means modify the plausible proportion of the statistics shown in example 9.
Some closing remarks.
It is perhaps unusual when concerning the observations and conclusions of an examination the author himself warns the audience. I emphasized in advance that the methods used in this paper might be risky to a certain extent. Already the retrieval of the information from the catalogs itself and the quasi-reconstruction of virtual sources by deduction is problematic. Already the material the analysis focused on is not beyond doubt reliable and what is more important it is only to a very limited extent suitable for analyzing the melodies in their real context. And the evaluation of the sources requires several aspects other than the mere occurrence or absence of a certain melody. For example, my own research proved that distribution of the Curiale melodies in the sources the assignment of them to certain feasts the pairing of them, the compilation of cycles from them and last but not least the actual variance of the melodies all together outline a physiognomy of repertory that could be characteristic of a diocese or a consuetudo. The other aspect I neglected here to a certain extent is the chronology. As Camilo Oswald, among others, emphasizes there is a not negligible difference between the 12th and 14th, 15th century state of the Aquileian tradition. Among my observations there may be cases where the differences are the consequences of chronological rather than geographical or institutional distance of the sources. However, the tables, presented in the foregoing, reveal the character of the Aquileian ordinary repertory, show its significant points and are quite promising as to make the picture more accurate and convincing later on by examining the other aspects mentioned above. Thank you very much.
